TensorFlow/Keras Imports¶

Explanation:¶

  • TensorFlow & Keras: The deep learning framework used for training the model.
  • Sequential API: Used to build the deep learning model layer by layer.
  • CNN Layers:
    • Conv2D: Convolutional layer for feature extraction.
    • MaxPooling2D: Reduces feature map size while retaining important features.
    • Flatten: Converts the 2D feature maps into a 1D vector.
    • Dense: Fully connected layer for classification.
    • Dropout: Reduces overfitting.
    • Rescaling: Normalizes input images.
  • MobileNet: Pre-trained CNN model chosen for classification.

Function to Get Class Distribution¶

Explanation:¶

  • Scans the dataset directory and counts how many images belong to each class.
  • Returns the top N most frequent classes.
  • Sorting ensures that the most frequent cancer types are included in training.
In [7]:
def get_class_distribution(data_dir, n_classes=3):
    """Get top n classes and their image counts"""
    class_counts = {}
    for class_name in os.listdir(data_dir):
        class_path = os.path.join(data_dir, class_name)
        if os.path.isdir(class_path):
            class_counts[class_name] = len(os.listdir(class_path))
    
    top_classes = sorted(class_counts.items(), key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)[:n_classes]
    
    print("\nFull Class Distribution:")
    print("-" * 40)
    for class_name, count in top_classes:
        print(f"{class_name} ({translate[class_name]}): {count} images")
    
    return [cls[0] for cls in top_classes]

Creating Data Generators¶

Explanation:¶

  • Prepares dataset for training:
    • Selects only the top classes.
    • Uses image_dataset_from_directory() to load images.
    • Splits into training (80%) and validation (20%).
    • Normalizes images (Rescaling(1./255)).
    • Uses caching & prefetching for optimized training.
In [8]:
def create_data_generators(data_dir='BrainImages', img_size=(224, 224), batch_size=32, n_images_per_class=0, number_of_classes=3):
    import shutil
    print("Creating data generators...")
    
    # Get top classes
    top_classes = get_class_distribution(data_dir, number_of_classes)
    print(f"\nUsing classes: {[f'{cls} ({translate[cls]})' for cls in top_classes]}")
    
    # Create a temporary directory for the selected classes
    #subset_dir = 'selected_classes'
    
    # Extract dataset type from data_dir
    dataset_type = os.path.basename(data_dir)  # Gets the last part of the path
    
    # Create a unique temporary directory name
    subset_dir = f'selected_classes_{dataset_type}'
    
    print(f"Creating temporary directory: {subset_dir}")   

    if os.path.exists(subset_dir):
        shutil.rmtree(subset_dir)
    os.makedirs(subset_dir)
    
    # Copy only the top classes
    for class_name in top_classes:
        src_path = os.path.join(data_dir, class_name)
        dst_path = os.path.join(subset_dir, class_name)
        
        os.makedirs(dst_path)
        images = sorted(os.listdir(src_path))
        
        if n_images_per_class > 0:
            images = images[:n_images_per_class]
        
        for img in images:
            src_file = os.path.join(src_path, img)
            dst_file = os.path.join(dst_path, img)
            shutil.copy2(src_file, dst_file)

    print("\nLoading training data...")
    train_ds = image_dataset_from_directory(
        subset_dir,
        validation_split=0.2,
        subset="training",
        seed=123,
        image_size=img_size,
        batch_size=batch_size
    )

    print("\nLoading validation data...")
    val_ds = image_dataset_from_directory(
        subset_dir,
        validation_split=0.2,
        subset="validation",
        seed=123,
        image_size=img_size,
        batch_size=batch_size
    )

    # Save class names before normalization
    class_names = train_ds.class_names

    # Add caching before normalization
    train_ds = train_ds.cache()
    val_ds = val_ds.cache()

    # Add normalization
    normalization_layer = Rescaling(1./255)
    
    # Add performance optimizations
    train_ds = train_ds.map(lambda x, y: (normalization_layer(x), y))
    train_ds = train_ds.prefetch(tf.data.AUTOTUNE)
    
    val_ds = val_ds.map(lambda x, y: (normalization_layer(x), y))
    val_ds = val_ds.prefetch(tf.data.AUTOTUNE)

    return train_ds, val_ds, subset_dir, class_names

Creating MobileNet-based CNN Model¶

Explanation:¶

  • Uses MobileNet as a feature extractor (pre-trained on ImageNet).
  • The base model’s layers are frozen to retain learned features.
  • Additional fully connected (Dense) layers are added:
    • 512 & 256 neurons with ReLU activation.
    • Dropout layers (0.5 & 0.3) to prevent overfitting.
    • Final Softmax layer for classification.
In [9]:
def create_model(input_shape, num_classes):
    """Create and return the CNN model using MobileNet"""
    base_model = MobileNet(  # Changed from VGG16 to MobileNet
        weights='imagenet', 
        include_top=False, 
        input_shape=input_shape
    )
    
    base_model.trainable = False
    
    model = Sequential([
        base_model,
        Flatten(),
        Dense(512, activation='relu'),
        Dropout(0.5),
        Dense(256, activation='relu'),
        Dropout(0.3),
        Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax')
    ])
    model.build((None,) + input_shape)
    
    return model

Compiling the Model¶

Explanation:¶

  • Calls create_model() and prints model summary.
  • Compiles model using:
    • Adam optimizer (learning rate = 0.0005).
    • Sparse categorical crossentropy (since labels are integers).
    • Accuracy as the main evaluation metric.
In [10]:
def setup_model(img_size, num_classes):
    """Creates and compiles the model with optimized settings"""
    # Create model as before
    model = create_model(
        input_shape=(img_size[0], img_size[1], 3),
        num_classes=num_classes
    )
    print("\nModel Summary:")
    model.summary()
    
    # Compile with optimized settings
    model.compile(
        optimizer=Adam(
            learning_rate=0.0005,  # Higher initial learning rate since we're using reduction
            beta_1=0.9,
            beta_2=0.999,
            epsilon=1e-07
        ),
        loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',
        metrics=['accuracy'],
        # jit_compile=True  # Disabled for MobileNet. This can be enabled for VGG16. Enable XLA compilation for faster training
    )
    
    return model

Setting Up Training Callbacks¶

Explanation:¶

  • ReduceLROnPlateau: Decreases learning rate if validation loss stops improving.
  • EarlyStopping: Stops training if validation loss doesn’t improve for 4 epochs.
  • These help prevent overfitting and improve model convergence.
In [11]:
def setup_training_callbacks():
    """Sets up training callbacks with both early stopping and learning rate reduction"""
    return [
        # Learning rate reduction callback
        keras.callbacks.ReduceLROnPlateau(
            monitor='val_loss',
            factor=0.5,      # Reduce LR by half
            patience=2,      # Wait 2 epochs before reducing
            min_lr=1e-6,     # Minimum LR threshold
            mode='min',
            verbose=1        # Print reduction messages
        ),
        # Early stopping with added parameters
        keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(
            monitor='val_loss',
            patience=4,      # Increased to give LR reduction a chance to work
            restore_best_weights=True,
            mode='min',
            verbose=1
        )
    ]

Training the Model¶

Explanation:¶

  • Calls model.fit() to start training.
  • Uses callbacks (EarlyStopping, ReduceLROnPlateau).
  • Returns training history (accuracy/loss per epoch).
In [12]:
def train_model_core(model, train_ds, val_ds, epochs, callbacks):
    """Core training function"""
    print("\nTraining model...")
    history = model.fit(
        train_ds,
        validation_data=val_ds,
        epochs=epochs,
        callbacks=callbacks
    )
    return history

Function to Train the Model¶

Explanation:¶

  • Handles the entire model training process, including:
    • Dataset loading using create_data_generators().
    • Model creation and compilation using setup_model().
    • Callback setup to prevent overfitting.
    • Training execution using model.fit().
  • Returns the trained model, training history, and dataset references.
In [13]:
def train_model(data_dir='BrainImages', img_size=(224, 224), batch_size=32, 
                epochs=20, n_images_per_class=0, number_of_classes=3):
    """Main orchestration function"""
    # 1. Setup data
    train_ds, val_ds, subset_dir, class_names = create_data_generators(
        data_dir=data_dir,
        img_size=img_size,
        batch_size=batch_size,
        n_images_per_class=n_images_per_class,
        number_of_classes=number_of_classes
    )
    
    # 2. Setup model
    model = setup_model(img_size, number_of_classes)
    
    # 3. Setup callbacks
    callbacks = setup_training_callbacks()
    
    # 4. Train model
    history = train_model_core(model, train_ds, val_ds, epochs, callbacks)
    
    return model, history, val_ds, class_names, subset_dir, train_ds

Function to Plot Training History¶

Explanation:¶

  • Plots training accuracy vs. validation accuracy and training loss vs. validation loss.
  • Accuracy: Measures how well the model predicts the correct class.
    • In a well-trained model, accuracy should increase over epochs.
    • If training accuracy increases but validation accuracy stagnates or drops, the model may be overfitting.
  • Loss: Measures the error in model predictions.
    • Loss should decrease over epochs for a well-performing model.
    • If validation loss increases while training loss decreases, the model is memorizing training data instead of generalizing.
  • Helps analyze model performance trends over time.
In [14]:
def plot_training_history(history):
    """Plot training history"""
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 4))
    
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    plt.plot(history.history['accuracy'])
    plt.plot(history.history['val_accuracy'])
    plt.title('Model Accuracy')
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
    plt.legend(['Train', 'Validation'])
    
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    plt.plot(history.history['loss'])
    plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'])
    plt.title('Model Loss')
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.ylabel('Loss')
    plt.legend(['Train', 'Validation'])
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

def print_dataset_summary(train_ds, val_ds, n_images_per_class, number_of_classes, batch_size):
    """Print detailed dataset statistics"""
    total_images = n_images_per_class * number_of_classes
    train_steps = len(train_ds)
    val_steps = len(val_ds)
    
    print("\nDataset Summary:")
    print(f"Images per class: {n_images_per_class}")
    print(f"Number of classes: {number_of_classes}")
    print(f"Total images: {total_images}")
    print(f"Training images: {len(train_ds) * batch_size}")
    print(f"Validation images: {len(val_ds) * batch_size}")
    print(f"Batch size: {batch_size}")
    print(f"Training steps per epoch: {train_steps}")
    print(f"Validation steps per epoch: {val_steps}")

Evaluating the Model¶

Explanation:¶

  • Computes model evaluation metrics:
    • Accuracy, Precision, Recall, F1 Score
    • Classification Report
  • Generates and plots evaluation graphs:
    • Confusion Matrix
    • ROC Curves
    • Precision-Recall Curves
  • Helps analyze the model’s classification performance across different cancer types.
In [16]:
def evaluate_model(model, val_ds, class_names):
    """Comprehensive model evaluation with ROC and PR curves"""
    # Get predictions
    all_predictions = []
    all_labels = []
    
    for images, labels in val_ds:
        predictions = model.predict(images, verbose=0)
        all_predictions.extend(predictions)
        all_labels.extend(labels.numpy())
    
    all_predictions = np.array(all_predictions)
    all_labels = np.array(all_labels)
    
    # Convert predictions to classes
    pred_classes = np.argmax(all_predictions, axis=1)
    
    # Calculate and print metrics
    print("\nModel Evaluation Metrics:")
    print("------------------------")
    accuracy = accuracy_score(all_labels, pred_classes)
    precision = precision_score(all_labels, pred_classes, average='weighted')
    recall = recall_score(all_labels, pred_classes, average='weighted')
    f1 = f1_score(all_labels, pred_classes, average='weighted')
    
    print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy:.4f}")
    print(f"Precision: {precision:.4f}")
    print(f"Recall: {recall:.4f}")
    print(f"F1 Score: {f1:.4f}")
    
    # Print classification report
    print("\nClassification Report:")
    print("---------------------")
    print(classification_report(all_labels, pred_classes, target_names=class_names))
    
    # Plot confusion matrix
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
    cm = confusion_matrix(all_labels, pred_classes)
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues',
                xticklabels=class_names, yticklabels=class_names)
    plt.title('Confusion Matrix')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.ylabel('True')
    plt.show()
    
    # Plot ROC curves
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
    for i, class_name in enumerate(class_names):
        # Convert to one-vs-rest binary classification
        y_true = (all_labels == i).astype(int)
        y_score = all_predictions[:, i]
        
        fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_true, y_score)
        roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)
        
        plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label=f'{class_name} (AUC = {roc_auc:.2f})')
    
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--')
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.title('ROC Curves')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()
    
    # Plot Precision-Recall curves
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
    for i, class_name in enumerate(class_names):
        y_true = (all_labels == i).astype(int)
        y_score = all_predictions[:, i]
        
        precision_curve, recall_curve, _ = precision_recall_curve(y_true, y_score)
        avg_precision = average_precision_score(y_true, y_score)
        
        plt.plot(recall_curve, precision_curve, 
                label=f'{class_name} (AP = {avg_precision:.2f})')
    
    plt.xlabel('Recall')
    plt.ylabel('Precision')
    plt.title('Precision-Recall Curves')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

Function to Show Sample Images¶

Explanation:¶

  • Displays a grid of sample images from each class in the dataset.
  • Helps visually verify that the dataset is correctly loaded before training.
  • Rescales images back to their original pixel range before displaying.
  • Uses Matplotlib to generate subplots with multiple images.
In [17]:
def show_sample_images(dataset, samples_per_class=3, class_names=None):
    """
    Display a grid of sample images from each class in the dataset.
    
    Args:
        dataset: TensorFlow dataset
        samples_per_class: Number of samples to show per class
        class_names: List of class names (optional)
    """
    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    
    # Get sample images for each class
    samples = {}
    for images, labels in dataset:
        for image, label in zip(images, labels):
            label = int(label)
            if label not in samples:
                samples[label] = []
            if len(samples[label]) < samples_per_class:
                # Rescale image back to [0,255] range
                image = image * 255.0
                samples[label].append(image)
        if all(len(imgs) >= samples_per_class for imgs in samples.values()):
            break

    # Set up the plot grid
    n_classes = len(samples)
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(n_classes, samples_per_class, 
                            figsize=(samples_per_class * 3, n_classes * 3))
    
    # Plot each sample
    for i, (label, images) in enumerate(samples.items()):
        for j, image in enumerate(images):
            ax = axes[i, j] if n_classes > 1 else axes[j]
            ax.imshow(image.numpy().astype("uint8"))
            ax.axis('off')
            if j == 0:
                title = f"Class {label}"
                if class_names and label < len(class_names):
                    title = class_names[label]
                ax.set_title(title, pad=10)

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Function to Plot Training History¶

Explanation:¶

  • Plots training accuracy vs. validation accuracy and training loss vs. validation loss.
  • Accuracy: Measures how well the model predicts the correct class.
    • In a well-trained model, accuracy should increase over epochs.
    • If training accuracy increases but validation accuracy stagnates or drops, the model may be overfitting.
  • Loss: Measures the error in model predictions.
    • Loss should decrease over epochs for a well-performing model.
    • If validation loss increases while training loss decreases, the model is memorizing training data instead of generalizing.
  • Helps analyze model performance trends over time.

Evaluating the Model¶

Explanation:¶

  • Computes performance metrics:
    • Accuracy, Precision, Recall, F1 Score.
    • Confusion Matrix to analyze misclassifications.
    • ROC and Precision-Recall curves for multi-class classification.
  • Helps assess how well the model performs on unseen validation data.

Understanding Evaluation Metrics¶

Accuracy¶

  • Measures the proportion of correctly classified instances.
  • Formula: Accuracy = (TP + TN) / (TP + TN + FP + FN)
  • Higher accuracy indicates better model performance but may not be reliable for imbalanced datasets.

Precision¶

  • Measures how many of the predicted positive cases are actually positive.
  • Formula: Precision = TP / (TP + FP)
  • High precision means fewer false positives.

Recall (Sensitivity)¶

  • Measures how many actual positive cases were correctly identified.
  • Formula: Recall = TP / (TP + FN)
  • High recall means fewer false negatives.

F1 Score¶

  • The harmonic mean of precision and recall.
  • Formula: F1 Score = 2 * (Precision * Recall) / (Precision + Recall)
  • Used when there is an imbalance between precision and recall.

Confusion Matrix¶

Explanation:¶

  • A table that summarizes the model's performance by comparing predicted vs. actual values.
  • Structure:
    • True Positives (TP): Correctly predicted positive cases.
    • True Negatives (TN): Correctly predicted negative cases.
    • False Positives (FP): Incorrectly predicted positives.
    • False Negatives (FN): Incorrectly predicted negatives.
  • Helps diagnose specific classification errors (e.g., false positives vs. false negatives).

ROC and Precision-Recall Curves for Multi-Class Classification¶

ROC (Receiver Operating Characteristic) Curve¶

  • Plots True Positive Rate (TPR) vs. False Positive Rate (FPR).
  • AUC (Area Under Curve) measures classification performance.
  • Higher AUC values indicate better classification ability.

Precision-Recall Curve¶

  • Plots Precision vs. Recall for different probability thresholds.
  • Useful for evaluating models on imbalanced datasets.
  • High precision-recall trade-off indicates good model generalization.

import numpy as np
import tensorflow as tf
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import cv2

# Extract the base MobileNet model from Sequential
base_model = model.layers[0]  # MobileNet is at index 0 inside Sequential

# Find the last Conv2D layer inside MobileNet
conv_layers = [layer for layer in base_model.layers if isinstance(layer, tf.keras.layers.Conv2D)]
if not conv_layers:
    raise ValueError("No Conv2D layers found in the base MobileNet model.")
last_conv_layer = conv_layers[-1]

# Define Grad-CAM model
grad_model = tf.keras.models.Model(
    inputs=base_model.input,
    outputs=[last_conv_layer.output, base_model.output]
)

Computing Grad-CAM¶

Explanation:¶

  • Implements Grad-CAM (Gradient-weighted Class Activation Mapping).
  • Highlights important image regions used by the model for classification.
  • Steps:
    1. Extracts feature maps from the last convolutional layer.
    2. Computes gradients of the target class with respect to feature maps.
    3. Averages gradients and weights feature maps accordingly.
    4. Generates heatmaps to overlay on original images.
In [27]:
def compute_gradcam(grad_model, img_array, last_conv_layer):
    """Computes Grad-CAM heatmap for an input image."""
    with tf.GradientTape() as tape:
        conv_output, predictions = grad_model(img_array)
        pred_class = tf.argmax(predictions[0]).numpy()  # Extract class index
        loss = tf.gather(predictions, pred_class, axis=-1)  # Fix shape issue

    grads = tape.gradient(loss, conv_output)
    pooled_grads = tf.reduce_mean(grads, axis=(0, 1, 2))

    conv_output = conv_output.numpy()[0]

    # Debugging: Print the shape of the last convolutional output
    print("Conv Output Shape:", conv_output.shape)  # <-- ADD THIS LINE
    heatmap = np.mean(conv_output * pooled_grads.numpy(), axis=-1)

    # Fix: Prevent NaN errors & ensure proper scaling
    eps = 1e-10
    heatmap = np.maximum(heatmap, 0)
    heatmap /= (np.max(heatmap) + eps)  # Normalize safely

    # Fix: Resize heatmap using TensorFlow for better alignment
    heatmap = tf.image.resize(heatmap[..., np.newaxis], (224, 224), method=tf.image.ResizeMethod.BICUBIC).numpy()
    heatmap = np.squeeze(heatmap)  # Remove extra dimension

    return heatmap

Overlaying Grad-CAM Heatmap¶

Explanation:¶

  • Merges the Grad-CAM heatmap with the original image.
  • Highlights critical regions that influenced the model's decision.
  • Uses color-mapping techniques to make the visualization clearer.
  • Ensures the overlay is aligned correctly for proper interpretation.
In [28]:
def overlay_gradcam(image_np, heatmap):
    """Overlays the Grad-CAM heatmap on an image with correct alignment."""
    heatmap = np.uint8(255 * heatmap)  # Convert to color range
    heatmap = cv2.applyColorMap(heatmap, cv2.COLORMAP_JET)

    # Fix: Ensure proper image format before overlaying
    if image_np.shape[-1] == 1:  # Convert grayscale to RGB if needed
        image_np = cv2.cvtColor(image_np, cv2.COLOR_GRAY2RGB)

    # Convert image from RGB to BGR (OpenCV uses BGR)
    image_bgr = cv2.cvtColor(image_np, cv2.COLOR_RGB2BGR)

    # Fix: Use cv2.addWeighted correctly
    overlay = cv2.addWeighted(image_bgr, 0.6, heatmap, 0.4, 0)

    # Convert back to RGB for correct visualization in Matplotlib
    return cv2.cvtColor(overlay, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)

Displaying Grad-CAM Results for Multiple Samples¶

Explanation:¶

  • Displays a grid of original images and their Grad-CAM overlays.
  • Helps verify whether the model is focusing on relevant tumor regions.
  • Uses Matplotlib to generate structured plots.
In [29]:
def show_gradcam_samples(dataset, samples_per_class=3, class_names=None):
    """
    Display a 3x3 grid of Grad-CAM visualizations for sample images from each class.

    Args:
        dataset: TensorFlow dataset
        samples_per_class: Number of samples to show per class
        class_names: List of class names (optional)
    """
    samples = {}

    for images, labels in dataset:
        for image, label in zip(images, labels):
            label = int(label)
            if label not in samples:
                samples[label] = []
            if len(samples[label]) < samples_per_class:
                samples[label].append(image)
        if all(len(imgs) >= samples_per_class for imgs in samples.values()):
            break

    fig, axes = plt.subplots(3, 3, figsize=(10, 10))  # 3x3 grid

    for i, (label, images) in enumerate(samples.items()):
        for j, image in enumerate(images):
            img_array = np.expand_dims(image, axis=0)

            # Convert image back to 0-255 range before Grad-CAM
            image_np = np.array(image * 255, dtype=np.uint8)

            # Compute Grad-CAM heatmap
            heatmap = compute_gradcam(grad_model, img_array, last_conv_layer)

            # Convert image to numpy format
            image_np = np.array(image * 255, dtype=np.uint8)

            # Generate Grad-CAM overlay
            overlay = overlay_gradcam(image_np, heatmap)

            ax = axes[i, j]
            ax.imshow(overlay)
            ax.axis('off')

            if j == 0:
                title = f"Class {label}"
                if class_names and label < len(class_names):
                    title = class_names[label]
                ax.set_title(title, pad=10)

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
